---
import Site from '../layouts/Site.astro';
import Waves from '../components/Waves.astro';
import { breadcrumb, jsonLdGraph } from '../lib/seo';

const lastUpdated = 'June 5, 2026';
const site = Astro.site!;
const jsonLd = jsonLdGraph(
  breadcrumb(site, [
    { name: 'Home', path: '/' },
    { name: 'Privacy Policy', path: '/privacy' },
  ]),
);
---

<Site
  title="Privacy Policy | nodrix"
  description="How nodrix — the open-source software you deploy — handles data. nodrix is self-hosted and single-tenant: your data stays in your own Cloudflare account; the software sends only anonymous, aggregate usage statistics about the deployment itself."
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script is:inline type="application/ld+json" set:html={jsonLd} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero-glow relative overflow-hidden border-b border-neutral-200/70">
    <Waves />
    <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-14 sm:px-6 sm:py-20">
      <span class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent-600">Legal</span>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 sm:text-5xl">Privacy Policy</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-neutral-600">
        How nodrix — the software you deploy — handles data.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-neutral-500">Last updated: {lastUpdated}</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-white">
    <div class="prose prose-neutral mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-12 sm:px-6 sm:py-16">
      <p>
        This Privacy Policy explains how nodrix — the open-source software you deploy — handles data.
        nodrix is self-hosted and single-tenant: it runs entirely within your own Cloudflare account,
        and all of your data stays there. The only information that ever leaves your deployment is
        anonymous, aggregate usage statistics about the instance itself (described in section 1) —
        never your data, and never anything that identifies you.
      </p>

      <h2>1. Anonymous usage statistics</h2>
      <p>
        So the project can tell how many self-hosted deployments exist and stay active, the nodrix
        worker sends a small anonymous usage ping to a project-operated collector
        (<code>telemetry.nodrix.live</code>): once when the owner account is first created, and then
        once a day.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each ping contains only a random instance identifier (not derived from you, your account, or
        your domain), the nodrix version, which integration types are configured, aggregate counts
        (such as the number of projects), and which features are enabled. It never contains IP
        addresses, your device telemetry or any variable values, the names of your projects,
        variables, or dashboards, account identifiers, email addresses, or any other personal data —
        and the collector does not log the request's IP. Because nodrix is open source, exactly what
        is sent can be verified in the source code. The data is anonymous and is sent automatically;
        there is no separate opt-out.
      </p>

      <h2>2. Where your data resides</h2>
      <p>
        nodrix is single-tenant. When you deploy it, the platform is provisioned into your own
        Cloudflare account, and all of your data — device telemetry, variables, dashboards,
        automations, and their history — is stored only in that account's Cloudflare D1, R2, Durable
        Objects, and KV. There is no nodrix-operated server between your devices and your deployment,
        and the project has no access to your instance or its data.
      </p>

      <h2>3. Data ownership and control</h2>
      <p>
        You own and control all data in your deployment. You determine how long it is retained, you
        can export it at any time through the read API, and you can delete it at any time by removing
        the relevant records or the underlying Cloudflare resources. Because the project never holds a
        copy of your data, there is nothing to request from us.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Processing on Cloudflare</h2>
      <p>
        nodrix runs on Cloudflare's infrastructure. Your deployment and the data it processes are
        therefore also subject to Cloudflare's terms of service and
        <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/privacypolicy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">privacy policy</a>;
        by deploying nodrix, you are using Cloudflare directly. The region in which your data is stored
        is determined by your own Cloudflare account and configuration.
      </p>

      <h2>5. Third-party integrations</h2>
      <p>
        If you configure integrations — for example email, webhooks, or chat services such as Slack,
        Telegram, or Discord — data you choose to send through them is transmitted to those providers
        and handled under their respective terms and privacy policies. You control which integrations
        are enabled and what they send.
      </p>

      <h2>6. Changes to this policy</h2>
      <p>
        We may update this Privacy Policy from time to time. Material changes will be reflected in the
        "Last updated" date shown above.
      </p>

      <h2>7. Contact</h2>
      <p>
        If you have questions about this policy, contact us at
        <a href="mailto:hello@nodrix.live">hello@nodrix.live</a>.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-12 rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-neutral-900">About this website</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-neutral-600">
          nodrix.live is our marketing website and is separate from the product described above. It is
          served through Cloudflare and uses Cloudflare Web Analytics — a privacy-first, cookieless
          measurement tool — along with Google Analytics to understand which pages are useful. These
          apply only while you browse this site, collect nothing about any nodrix deployment, and can
          be blocked with your browser or a privacy extension.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Site>
